<h4>
  Idetnifying the Agent and Object of a Force
</h4>

<p class = 'definition' data-word = 'Agent of a Force'>
  Every force must have an <strong>agent</strong>.
  The agent is the thing causing the force.
  The agent <em>must</em> be something physical and real, something you can touch.
  <br>
  It is a good pratice to always identify the agent of a force.
</p>
<p class = 'definition' data-word = 'Object of a Force'>
  Every force must have an <strong>object</strong>.
  The object is the thing receiving the force.
  The object <em>must</em> be something physical and real, something you can touch.
  <br>
  It is a good pratice to always identify the object of a force.
  On a free-body daigram, all forces have the same object.
</p>


<h5>
  Examples
</h5>

<ul>
  <li>
    Mike punches Evander in the face.
    The agent of the force is Mike's fist,
    and the object is Evander's face.
  </li>
  <li>
    Gravity is pulling down on a baseball.
    The agent of the force is the earth,
    and the object of the force is the baseball.
  </li>
  <li>
    Joey is lying in bed.
    The normal force is holding him up.
    The agent of this force is the bed,
    and the object of the force is Joey.
  </li>
</ul>

