<h4>
  Balanced Force Pairs
</h4>

<p>
  In order to master physics, you need to learn to identify
  all action-reaction force pairs.
  Unfortunately for students of physics, in most problems,
  there are <em>other pairs</em> of forces that
  <em>also</em> have equal magnitude and opposite direction,
  but aren't action-reaction force pairs.
  &#x1f615;
  &#x1f615;
  &#x1f615;
</p>

<p>
  Therefore, in this lesson we are going to also identify <em>balanced force pairs</em>.
</p>

<p class = 'definition' data-answer = 'Balanced Force Pairs'>
  A balanced force pair are a pair of forces
  with equal magnitude and opposite direction that
  act on the <em>same object</em>.
  <br>
  They usually consist of one force with definite magnitude
  and another force with adjustable magnitude called a <em>constraint force</em>.
</p>

<h5>
  How to Identify Balanced Force Pairs
</h5>

<ul>
  <li>
    Balanced force pairs appear on the <em>same</em> free-body diagram.
  </li>
  <li>
    Balanced forces occur when an object has net force zero in
    either the X or Y dimension.
  </li>
  <li>
    Usually, one of the two balanced forces is a <em>constraint force</em>.
    A constraint force is a force that does not have a particular magnitude
    but adjusts its magnitude to match a particular situation.
    The most common constraint forces are normal force, tension (sometimes), and static friction.
  </li>
</ul>



